te [[Eugene W. Chafin|Eugene Chafin]] received 41 votes, and [[Socialist Labor Party of America|Socialist Labor]] candidate [[Arthur E. Reimer|Arthur Reimer]] received 5 votes.</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[1908 United States presidential election|1908]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''62.0%''' ''2,704''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|33.3% ''1,453''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|4.7% ''204''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[1904 United States presidential election|1904]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''66.6%''' ''2,864''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|29.3% ''1,260''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|4.1% ''177''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[1900 United States presidential election|1900]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''61.9%''' ''2,715''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|34.7% ''1,522''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|3.3% ''146''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[1896 United States presidential election|1896]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''60.2%''' ''2,655''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|37.9% ''1,674''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|1.9% ''84''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[1892 United States presidential election|1892]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''55.7%''' ''2,100''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|33.6% ''1,264''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|10.7% ''404''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[1888 United States presidential election|1888]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''61.1%''' ''2,352''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|35.0% ''1,348''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|3.9% ''148''\n|}\n{{Hidden end}}\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1840= 2578\n|1850= 6104\n|1860= 10374\n|1870= 12854\n|1880= 14645\n|1890= 14478\n|1900= 15219\n|1910= 14274\n|1920= 13360\n|1930= 13386\n|1940= 13740\n|1950= 17087\n|1960= 17184\n|1970= 20159\n|1980= 24694\n|1990= 27446\n|2000= 33214\n|2010= 34185\n|estyear=2019\n|estimate=34594\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=July 26, 2019}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=July 10, 2014}}</ref><br />1790-1960<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mapserver.lib.virginia.edu|title=Historical Census Browser|publisher=University of Virginia Library|accessdate=July 10, 2014}}</ref> 1900-1990<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/cencounts/in190090.txt|title=Population of Counties by Decennial Census: 1900 to 1990|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=July 10, 2014}}</ref><br />1990-2000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/cen2000/briefs/phc-t4/tables/tab02.pdf|title=Census 2000 PHC-T-4. Ranking Tables for Counties: 1990 and 2000|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=July 10, 2014}}</ref> 2010-2013<ref name=\"census-quickfacts\"/>\n}}\n\nAs of the [[2010 United States Census]], there were 34,185&nbsp;people, 13,310&nbsp;households, and 9,153&nbsp;families residing in the county.<ref name=\"census-dp1\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/DPDP1/0500000US18151\n  |title=DP-1 Profile of General Population and Housing Characteristics: 2010 Demographic Profile Data\n  |accessdate=2015-07-10\n  |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]\n  |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213015718/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/DPDP1/0500000US18151\n  |archive-date=2020-02-13\n  |url-status=dead\n  }}</ref> The population density was {{convert|110.7|PD/sqmi}}. There were 19,377 housing units at an average density of {{convert|62.7|/sqmi}}.<ref name=\"census-density\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/GCTPH1.CY10/0500000US18151\n  |accessdate=2015-07-10\n  |title=Population, Housing Units, Area, and Density: 2010 - County\n  |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]\n  |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212200157/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/GCTPH1.CY10/0500000US18151\n  |archive-date=2020-02-12\n  |url-status=dead\n  }}</ref> The racial makeup of the county was 96.8% white, 0.5% black or African American, 0.5% Asian, 0.3% American Indian, 0.9% from other races, and 0.9% from two or more races. Those of Hispanic or Latino origin made up 2.9% of the population.<ref name=\"census-dp1\"/> In terms of ancestry, 37.8% were [[Germans|German]], 12.6% were [[English people|English]], 10.5% were [[Irish people|Irish]], and 8.2% were [[Americans|American]].<ref name=\"census-dp2\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP02/0400000US18%7c0500000US18151\n  |title=DP02 SELECTED SOCIAL CHARACTERISTICS IN THE UNITED STATES \u2013 2006-2010 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates\n  |accessdate=2015-07-10\n  |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]\n  |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200214003521/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP02/0400000US18%7C0500000US18151\n  |archive-date=2020-02-14\n  |url-status=dead\n  }}</ref>\n\nOf the 13,310&nbsp;households, 30.4% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 54.3% were married couples living together, 9.3% had a female householder with no husband present, 31.2% were non-families, and 25.3% of all households were made up of individuals. The average household size was 2.47 and the average family size was 2.94. The median age was 40.2 years.<ref name=\"census-dp1\"/>\n\nThe median income for a household in the county was $47,697 and the median income for a family was $57,154. Males had a median income of $40,833 versus $29,614 for females. The per capita income for the county was $22,950. About 7.7% of families and 10.9% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 16.4% of those under age 18 and 6.3% of those age 65 or over.<ref name=\"census-dp3\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP03/0400000US18%7c0500000US18151\n  |title=DP03 SELECTED ECONOMIC CHARACTERISTICS \u2013 2006-2010 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates\n  |accessdate=2015-07-10\n  |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]\n  |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200214004055/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP03/0400000US18%7C0500000US18151\n  |archive-date=2020-02-14\n  |url-status=dead\n  }}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\n\n=== Colleges and universities ===\n* [[Trine University]]\n\n[[Image:Fremont, Indiana High School.jpg|thumb|350px|right|Fremont High School]]\n\n=== School districts ===\n* Fremont Community Schools\n* Hamilton Community Schools\n* M S D of Steuben County\n* Prairie Heights Community School Corporation\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Edgar Buell|Edgar \"Pop\" Buell]] (1913\u20131980), humanitarian aid worker in [[Laos]] in the 1960s and 1970s, was born in [[Richland Township, Steuben County, Indiana|Richland Township]] and farmed there until he joined [[International Voluntary Services]] in 1960.<ref>See 1920 Federal Census, Richland Township, Steuben County, Indiana, page 5B, Enumeration District 161; and; [http://www.vietnam.ttu.edu/star/images/239/2390902003A.pdf ''Theory and Practice of Communism in 1972 (Southeast Asia),'' Part I. Hearings of the House Committee on Internal Security, May 25, 1972, on northeastern Laos. pp. 1-4, 7761-7817. Testimony of Edgar M. Buell].</ref>\n* [[Sile Doty]], infamous [[robber]], [[burglar]], [[horse thief]], [[highwayman]], [[counterfeit money|counterfeiter]], and criminal gang leader.\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[The Herald Republican]]'', daily newspaper covering Steuben County\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Steuben County, Indiana]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.steubencounty.com/ Official Site of Steuben County, Indiana]\n* [http://www.lakes101.org/ Steuben County Tourism Bureau]\n* [http://www.steubenfoundation.org/ Steuben County Community Foundation]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051020012801/http://www.steuben.lib.in.us/ Carnegie Public Library of Steuben County]\n* [http://www.rootsweb.com/~insteube/ Steuben County Genealogical Society]\n\n{{Geographic Location\n|Centre    = Steuben County, Indiana\n|North     = [[Branch County, Michigan]]\n|Northeast = [[Hillsdale County, Michigan]]\n|East      = [[Williams County, Ohio]]\n|Southeast =\n|South     = [[DeKalb County, Indiana|DeKalb County]]\n|Southwest = [[Noble County, Indiana|Noble County]]\n|West      = [[LaGrange County, Indiana|LaGrange County]]\n|Northwest =\n}}\n{{Steuben County, Indiana}}\n{{Indiana}}\n\n{{coord|41.64|-85.00|display=title|type:adm2nd_region:US-IN_source:UScensus1990}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Steuben County, Indiana| ]]\n[[Category:Indiana counties]]\n[[Category:1837 establishments in Indiana]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1837]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox U.S. county\n| county          = Steuben County\n| state           = Indiana\n| seal            = \n| founded year    = 1837\n| founded date    = \n| seat wl         = Angola\n| largest city wl = Angola\n| area_total_sq_mi = 322.47\n| area_land_sq_mi = 308.94\n| area_water_sq_mi = 13.53\n| area percentage = 4.20%\n| census estimate yr = 2018\n| pop             = 34586\n| density_sq_mi      = 111\n| density_km2      = 42.75\n| time zone       = Eastern\n| website             = [http://www.steubencounty.com/ Official Site of Steuben County, Indiana]\n| named for       = [[Friedrich Wilhelm von Steuben|Baron Frederick von Steuben]]\n| district = 3rd\n| ex image        =  Steuben Co IN Courthouse.jpg\n| ex image size   =  250px\n| ex image cap    =  Steuben County Courthouse, in Angola, Indiana.  The courthouse is on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].  For a list of all such sites in Steuben County, see [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Steuben County, Indiana]].\n| footnotes = Indiana county number 76\n}}\n\n'''Steuben County''' is a [[County (United States)|county]] located in the northeast corner of the [[U.S. state]] of [[Indiana]].  The county was named after [[Friedrich Wilhelm von Steuben|Baron von Steuben]], a [[Kingdom of Prussia|Prussian]] military officer who helped train the [[Continental Army]] during the [[American Revolutionary War]].\n\nThe [[county seat]] is [[Angola, Indiana|Angola]].<ref name=\"GR6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx|accessdate=2011-06-07|title=Find a County|publisher=National Association of Counties}}</ref> The area was developed for agriculture in the 19th century and has many natural resources. The county contains a state park and 105 lakes of various sizes.  Some of the larger lakes are [[Lake James (Indiana)|Lake James]], [[Lake George (Steuben County, Indiana)|Lake George]], Clear Lake, Jimmerson Lake, Lake Gage, and Crooked Lake.  As of 2010, the county population was 34,185.<ref name=\"census-quickfacts\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/18/18151.html\n  |title=Steuben County QuickFacts\n  |accessdate=2011-09-25\n  |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]}}</ref>\n\nSteuben County comprises the Angola, IN [[Micropolitan Statistical Area]].\n\n==History==\nThis area was historically occupied by the [[Potawatomi]] people, who were one of the three tribes in the [[Council of Three Fires]]. Typically they lived in highly decentralized bands. Treaties signed by some leaders with United States representatives ceded large areas of their territory to the US.\n\nSteuben County was officially created by European Americans in 1837 from [[LaGrange County, Indiana|LaGrange County]], and named for [[Friedrich Wilhelm von Steuben|Baron Frederick von Steuben]], an officer of the [[American Revolutionary War]].<ref>{{cite book|author=De Witt Clinton Goodrich & Charles Richard Tuttle|publisher=R. S. Peale & co.|year=1875|location=Indiana|title=An Illustrated History of the State of Indiana|url=https://archive.org/details/anillustratedhi02tuttgoog| pages=[https://archive.org/details/anillustratedhi02tuttgoog/page/n585 573]}}</ref> In 1840 the Potawatomi were forcibly removed from this area and neighboring territory in Michigan and Ohio to Indian Territory in Kansas.\n\nA Potawatomi chief, [[Baw Beese]], led a band that was based at what later became known as Baw Beese Lake nearby in Michigan. His daughter Winona married Negnaska and lived in what is now Indiana. She was executed in the 1830s by her husband's people after she killed Negnaska for selling her pony.<ref name=\"Winona Story\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=gCDiAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA582 Fuller, George Newman and Beeson, Lewis]''Michigan History Vol. 6'' Lansing: Michigan State Historical Society, 1922. p. 582</ref> Winona's husband had pledged his rifle to Aaron B. Goodwin of [[Fremont, Indiana]] for the use of a 5-gallon keg. The Indians had the keg filled with whiskey at Nichols' store in Jamestown, and he took all the money they had. Negnaska sold his wife Winona's pony in order to pawn his rifle. Winona owned the pony outright, either as a gift from her father or having bought it with her own money. She killed Negnaska in anger for selling what was hers. Winona was held by the tribe for a few hours, until her husband's nearest relative arrived to execute her. As was their custom, he stabbed her to the heart as she had her husband.<ref name=\"Winona History\"/>\n\t\nJohn D. Barnard and Sheldon Havens were said to have encountered the Potawatomi group after the execution; they helped them move the bodies to a nearby grave that had been dug. The Indians did not bury the bodies until after the white men were out of sight. But Dr. B.F. Sheldon found out about it and exhumed the bodies for dissection a few days later, outraging the mourning Potawatomi. About two weeks later some Potawatomi returned the keg to Goodwin and tried to retrieve Negnaska's rifle, but Goodwin pretended not to know the man had been killed and refused to release the rifle to his friends.<ref name=\"Winona History\">[https://archive.org/stream/historyofsteuben00inte/historyofsteuben00inte_djvu.txt ''History of Steuben County, Indiana''], Chicago: Inter-state Publishing Company, 1885. pp. 550-551.</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:SteubenCountyIndiana.JPG|thumb|right|500px|alt=map with highways and lakes|Steuben County and its lakes]]According to the 2010 census, the county has a total area of {{convert|322.47|sqmi}}, of which {{convert|308.94|sqmi}} (or 95.80%) is land and {{convert|13.53|sqmi}} (or 4.20%) is water.<ref name=\"census-density\"/>\n\n===Cities and towns===\n*[[Angola, Indiana|Angola]]\n*[[Ashley, Indiana|Ashley]]\n*[[Clear Lake, Indiana|Clear Lake]]\n*[[Fremont, Indiana|Fremont]]\n*[[Hamilton, Indiana|Hamilton]]\n*[[Hudson, Indiana|Hudson]]\n*[[Orland, Indiana|Orland]]\n*[[Pleasant Lake, Indiana|Pleasant Lake]]\n\n===Unincorporated towns===\n{|\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|\n*[[Alvarado, Indiana|Alvarado]]\n*[[Berlien, Indiana|Berlien]]\n*[[Circle Park, Indiana|Circle Park]]\n*[[Clarks Landing, Indiana|Clarks Landing]]\n*[[Cold Springs, Steuben County, Indiana|