n|1850= 6104\n|1860= 10374\n|1870= 12854\n|1880= 14645\n|1890= 14478\n|1900= 15219\n|1910= 14274\n|1920= 13360\n|1930= 13386\n|1940= 13740\n|1950= 17087\n|1960= 17184\n|1970= 20159\n|1980= 24694\n|1990= 27446\n|2000= 33214\n|2010= 34185\n|estyear=2019\n|estimate=34594\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=July 26, 2019}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=July 10, 2014}}</ref><br />1790-1960<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mapserver.lib.virginia.edu|title=Historical Census Browser|publisher=University of Virginia Library|accessdate=July 10, 2014}}</ref> 1900-1990<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/cencounts/in190090.txt|title=Population of Counties by Decennial Census: 1900 to 1990|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=July 10, 2014}}</ref><br />1990-2000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/cen2000/briefs/phc-t4/tables/tab02.pdf|title=Census 2000 PHC-T-4. Ranking Tables for Counties: 1990 and 2000|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=July 10, 2014}}</ref> 2010-2013<ref name=\"census-quickfacts\"/>\n}}\n\nAs of the [[2010 United States Census]], there were 34,185&nbsp;people, 13,310&nbsp;households, and 9,153&nbsp;families residing in the county.<ref name=\"census-dp1\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/DPDP1/0500000US18151\n  |title=DP-1 Profile of General Population and Housing Characteristics: 2010 Demographic Profile Data\n  |accessdate=2015-07-10\n  |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]\n  |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213015718/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/DPDP1/0500000US18151\n  |archive-date=2020-02-13\n  |url-status=dead\n  }}</ref> The population density was {{convert|110.7|PD/sqmi}}. There were 19,377 housing units at an average density of {{convert|62.7|/sqmi}}.<ref name=\"census-density\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/GCTPH1.CY10/0500000US18151\n  |accessdate=2015-07-10\n  |title=Population, Housing Units, Area, and Density: 2010 - County\n  |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]\n  |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212200157/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/GCTPH1.CY10/0500000US18151\n  |archive-date=2020-02-12\n  |url-status=dead\n  }}</ref> The racial makeup of the county was 96.8% white, 0.5% black or African American, 0.5% Asian, 0.3% American Indian, 0.9% from other races, and 0.9% from two or more races. Those of Hispanic or Latino origin made up 2.9% of the population.<ref name=\"census-dp1\"/> In terms of ancestry, 37.8% were [[Germans|German]], 12.6% were [[English people|English]], 10.5% were [[Irish people|Irish]], and 8.2% were [[Americans|American]].<ref name=\"census-dp2\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP02/0400000US18%7c0500000US18151\n  |title=DP02 SELECTED SOCIAL CHARACTERISTICS IN THE UNITED STATES \u2013 2006-2010 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates\n  |accessdate=2015-07-10\n  |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]\n  |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200214003521/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP02/0400000US18%7C0500000US18151\n  |archive-date=2020-02-14\n  |url-status=dead\n  }}</ref>\n\nOf the 13,310&nbsp;households, 30.4% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 54.3% were married couples living together, 9.3% had a female householder with no husband present, 31.2% were non-families, and 25.3% of all households were made up of individuals. The average household size was 2.47 and the average family size was 2.94. The median age was 40.2 years.<ref name=\"census-dp1\"/>\n\nThe median income for a household in the county was $47,697 and the median income for a family was $57,154. Males had a median income of $40,833 versus $29,614 for females. The per capita income for the county was $22,950. About 7.7% of families and 10.9% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 16.4% of those under age 18 and 6.3% of those age 65 or over.<ref name=\"census-dp3\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP03/0400000US18%7c0500000US18151\n  |title=DP03 SELECTED ECONOMIC CHARACTERISTICS \u2013 2006-2010 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates\n  |accessdate=2015-07-10\n  |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]\n  |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200214004055/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP03/0400000US18%7C0500000US18151\n  |archive-date=2020-02-14\n  |url-status=dead\n  }}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\n\n=== Colleges and universities ===\n*[[Trine University]]\n\n[[Image:Fremont, Indiana High School.jpg|thumb|350px|right|Fremont High School]]\n\n=== School districts ===\n*Fremont Community Schools\n*Hamilton Community Schools\n*M S D of Steuben County\n*Prairie Heights Community School Corporation\n\n==Notable people==\n\n*[[Edgar Buell|Edgar \"Pop\" Buell]] (1913\u20131980), humanitarian aid worker in [[Laos]] in the 1960s and 1970s, was born in [[Richland Township, Steuben County, Indiana|Richland Township]] and farmed there until he joined [[International Voluntary Services]] in 1960.<ref>See 1920 Federal Census, Richland Township, Steuben County, Indiana, page 5B, Enumeration District 161; and; [http://www.vietnam.ttu.edu/star/images/239/2390902003A.pdf ''Theory and Practice of Communism in 1972 (Southeast Asia),'' Part I. Hearings of the House Committee on Internal Security, May 25, 1972, on northeastern Laos. pp. 1-4, 7761-7817. Testimony of Edgar M. Buell].</ref>\n*[[Sile Doty]], infamous [[robber]], [[burglar]], [[horse thief]], [[highwayman]], [[counterfeit money|counterfeiter]], and criminal gang leader.\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[The Herald Republican]]'', daily newspaper covering Steuben County\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Steuben County, Indiana]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.steubencounty.com/ Official Site of Steuben County, Indiana]\n*[http://www.lakes101.org/ Steuben County Tourism Bureau]\n*[http://www.steubenfoundation.org/ Steuben County Community Foundation]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20051020012801/http://www.steuben.lib.in.us/ Carnegie Public Library of Steuben County]\n*[http://www.rootsweb.com/~insteube/ Steuben County Genealogical Society]\n\n{{Geographic Location\n|Centre    = Steuben County, Indiana\n|North     = [[Branch County, Michigan]]\n|Northeast = [[Hillsdale County, Michigan]]\n|East      = [[Williams County, Ohio]]\n|Southeast = \n|South     = [[DeKalb County, Indiana|DeKalb County]]\n|Southwest = [[Noble County, Indiana|Noble County]]\n|West      = [[LaGrange County, Indiana|LaGrange County]]\n|Northwest = \n}}\n{{Steuben County, Indiana}}\n{{Indiana}}\n\n{{coord|41.64|-85.00|display=title|type:adm2nd_region:US-IN_source:UScensus1990}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Steuben County, Indiana| ]]\n[[Category:Indiana counties]]\n[[Category:1837 establishments in Indiana]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1837]]\n", "name_user": "Whoisjohngalt", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleaned up usingAutoEd", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steuben_County,_Indiana"}
{"title_page": "Pamela Austin", "text_new": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{distinguish|text=the tennis player [[Pam Austin]]}}\n{{One source|date=April 2012}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Use American English|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                    = Pamela Austin\n| image                   =\n| caption                 =\n| birth_name              = Pamela Joan Akert\n| birth_date              = {{Birth date and age|1941|12|20}}\n| birth_place             = [[Omaha, Nebraska]], U.S.\n| occupation              = Actor\n| years_active            = 1961\u20131988\n| spouse                  = {{marriage|Charles W. Britt|1963|1964}}<br>{{marriage|Guy Franklin McElwaine|1965|1967}}<br>{{marriage|Leopold S. Wyler|1974}}\n}}\n\n'''Pamela Austin''' (born '''Pamela Joan Akert''', December 20, 1941) is an American actress.\n\n==Early life==\nAustin was born in [[Omaha, Nebraska]]. She spent part of her childhood in Europe, as her father served a tour of duty with the Air Force there. Austin studied dancing at [[California State University, Sacramento|Sacramento State College]], and found work with the Tony Martin nightclub act upon arriving in Hollywood.<ref name=\"glamourgirlsofthesilverscreen\">{{cite web|url=http://www.glamourgirlsofthesilverscreen.com/show/521/Pamela+Austin/index.html|title=Pamela Austin profile|publisher=glamourgirlsofthesilverscreen.com|accessdate=April 19, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nNatalia aka BEANBEAR loves her brother Diego so much and this is Wikipedia so it must be true right TALIA??? <3\n\n\nIn addition to appearing in two [[Elvis Presley]] films, in 1965-1967 Austin gained fame for a long series of popular automobile television commercials (and print ads) for [[Dodge]] (the [[Dodge Charger|Charger]], [[Dodge Coronet|Coronet]], [[Dodge Polara|Polara]], and other models). As the perky \"Dodge Rebellion Girl\", she appeared in around twenty commercials as a [[damsel in distress]] \u2014 menaced by sharks, falling from a draw-bridge, a roof, a cargo plane, etc. Her tag line at the end of each ad was \"The Dodge Rebellion wants you!\"{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\nThe ad series led to numerous film and television offers and a three-page profile in ''[[TV Guide]]'' (August 20\u201326, 1966). By 1968, Dodge executives felt Austin's popularity was overshadowing the cars and began a new \"Dodge Fever\" campaign with a different model, Joan Anita Parker.\n\nIn August 1967 she starred in the adventure-comedy film ''[[The Perils of Pauline (1967 film)|The Perils of Pauline]]'' based on the silent [[cliff-hanger]] [[Serial film|serial]]. Posters for the film referenced her Dodge commercials: ''That \"Rebellion Girl\" is dodgin' unbelievable perils...''<ref>[https://movies.nytimes.com/person/2899/Pamela-Austin/filmography Filmography], nytimes.com; accessed January 6, 2017.</ref>\n\nIn 1968 she was a semi-regular on the hit comedy series ''[[Rowan & Martin's Laugh-In]]'' during its first season. Austin performed in various comedy sketches, song-and-dance numbers, and pre-filmed segments, including an early music video for \"Buy For Me The Rain\" by [[The Nitty Gritty Dirt Band]].<ref>{{IMDb name|0042487}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Films===\n*''[[Blue Hawaii]]'' (1961) - Selena (Sandy) Emerson\n*''[[The Chapman Report]]'' (1962)\n*''[[Rome Adventure]]'' (1962) - Agnes Hutton\n*''[[Critic's Choice (film)|Critic's Choice]]'' (1963) - Daughter (uncredited)\n*''[[The Caretakers]]'' (1963) - Student Nurse (uncredited)\n*''[[Hootenanny Hoot]]'' (1963) - Billie-Jo Henley\n*''[[Kissin' Cousins]]'' (1964) - Selena Tatum\n*''[[The Perils of Pauline (1967 film)|The Perils of Pauline]]'' (1967) - Pauline\n*''[[Evil Roy Slade]]'' (1972, TV Movie) - Betsy Potter\n*''[[Agatha (film)|Agatha]]'' (1979) - Pierrot #2\n*''[[No Surrender (film)|No Surrender]]'' (1985) - Organist\n*''[[The Dressmaker (1988 film)|The Dressmaker]]'' (1988) - Singer (final film role)\n\n===Television===\n*''[[Screenplay (TV series)|Screenplay]]'' (1980)\n*''[[List of Columbo episodes#Season 1|Columbo: Blueprint for Murder]]'' (1972)\n*''[[Love American Style]]'' (\"Love and the Phone Booth\"; 1969)\n*''[[Rowan & Martin's Laugh-In]]'' (six episodes; 1968)\n*''[[It Takes a Thief (1968 TV series)|It Takes a Thief]]'' (\"Hans Across the Border\", part 1 & 2) (1968)\n*''[[The Virginian (TV series)|The Virginian]]'' (\"Girl on the Glass Mountain\") (1966)\n*''[[The Wild Wild West]]'' (\"The Night of the Whirring Death\"; 1966)\n*''[[My Three Sons]]''  (\"Robbie and the Chorus Girl\"; 1965)\n*''[[The Twilight Zone (1959 TV series)|The Twilight Zone]]'' (\"[[Number 12 Looks Just Like You]]\"; 1964)\n*''[[The Fugitive (TV series)|The Fugitive]]'' (\"Come Watch Me Die\"; 1964)\n*''[[Wagon Train]]'' (\"Molly Kincaid Story\"; 1963)\n*''[[77 Sunset Strip]]'' (\"Reunion at Balboa\"; 1963) \n*''[[77 Sunset Strip]]'' (\"The Steerer\"; 1962) \n*''[[Surfside 6]]'' (\"Prescription for Panic\"; 1961)\n*''[[Lawman (TV series)|Lawman]]'' (\"Jailbreak\";1962)\n\n==Personal life==\nAustin married Charles W. Britt in Santa Clara, California on October 27, 1963; they had one child, a son, Beau C. Britt (born June 17, 1964). Austin and Britt divorced later that year.\n\nShe married, secondly, to Guy Franklin McElwaine (a Hollywood press agent) in Los Angeles on July 17, 1965. They divorced in June 1967. She married Leopold S. Wyler in Los Angeles on January 9, 1974.<ref name=\"glamourgirlsofthesilverscreen\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0042487}}\n*{{IBDB name|97958}}\n*{{Youtube|tZQbuk6_opE|1966 Dodge Rebellion campaign promo}}\n*{{Youtube|Dg8HN7Ht_TA|1967 Dodge Polara advertisement featuring Pamela Austin}}\n*{{Youtube|NTf9GdsMahI|1967 Dodge Dart TV ad & Pamela Austin tribute}}\n*[http://elviswomen.greggers.net/austinpam.htm Fansite profile]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Austin, Pamela}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Omaha, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{distinguish|text=the tennis player [[Pam Austin]]}}\n{{One source|date=April 2012}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Use American English|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                    = Pamela Austin\n| image                   =\n| caption                 =\n| birth_name              = Pamela Joan Akert\n| birth_date              = {{Birth date and age|1941|12|20}}\n| birth_place             = [[Omaha, Nebraska]], U.S.\n| occupation              = Actor\n| years_active            = 1961\u20131988\n| spouse                  = {{marriage|Charles W. Britt|1963|1964}}<br>{{marriage|Guy Franklin McElwaine|1965|1967}}<br>{{marriage|Leopold S. Wyler|1974}}\n}}\n\n'''Pamela Austin''' (born '''Pamela Joan Akert''', December 20, 1941) is an American actress.\n\n==Early life==\nAustin was born in [[Omaha, Nebraska]]. She spent part of her childhood in Europe, as her father served a tour of duty with the Air Force there. Austin studied dancing at [[California State University, Sacramento|Sacramento State College]], and found work with the Tony Martin nightclub act upon arriving in Hollywood.<ref name=\"glamourgirlsofthesilverscreen\">{{cite web|url=http://www.glamourgirlsofthesilverscreen.com/show/521/Pamela+Austin/index.html|title=Pamela Austin profile|publisher=glamourgirlsofthesilverscreen.com|accessdate=April 19, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn addition to appearing in two [[Elvis Presley]] films, in 1965-1967 Austin gained fame for a long series of popular automobile television commercials (and print ads) for [[Dodge]] (the [[Dodge Charger|Charger]], [[Dodge Coronet|Coronet]], [[Dodge Polara|Polara]], and other models). As the perky \"Dodge Rebellion Girl\", she appeared in around twenty commercials as a [[damsel in distress]] \u2014 menaced by sharks, falling from a draw-bridge, a roof, a cargo plane, etc. Her tag line at the end of each ad was \"The Dodge Rebellion wants you!\"{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\nThe ad series led to numerous film and television offers and a three-page profile in ''[[TV Guide]]'' (August 20\u201326, 1966). By 1968, Dodge executives felt Austin's popularity was overshadowing the cars and began a new \"Dodge Fever\" campaign with a different model, Joan Anita Parker.\n\nIn August 1967 she starred in the adventure-comedy film ''[[The Perils of Pauline (1967 film)|The Perils of Pauline]]'' based on the silent [[cliff-hanger]] [[Serial film|serial]]. Posters for the film referenced her Dodge commercials: ''That \"Rebellion Girl\" is dodgin' unbelievable perils...''<ref>[https://movies.nytimes.com/person/2899/Pamela-Austin/filmography Filmography], nytimes.com; accessed January 6, 2017.</ref>\n\nIn 1968 she was a semi-regular on the hit comedy series ''[[Rowan & Martin's Laugh-In]]'' during its first season. Austin performed in various comedy sketches, song-and-dance numbers, and pre-filmed segments, including an early music video for \"Buy For Me The Rain\" by [[The Nitty Gritty Dirt Band]].<ref>{{IMDb name|0042487}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Films===\n*''[[Blue Hawaii]]'' (1961) - Selena (Sandy) Emerson\n*''[[The Chapman Report]]'' (1962)\n*''[[Rome Adventure]]'' (1962) - Agnes Hutton\n*''[[Critic's Choice (film)|Critic's Choice]]'' (1963) - Daughter (uncredited)\n*''[[The Caretakers]]'' (1963) - Student Nurse (uncredited)\n*''[[Hootenanny Hoot]]'' (1963) - Billie-Jo Henley\n*''[[Kissin' Cousins]]'' (1964) - Selena Tatum\n*''[[The Perils of Pauline (1967 film)|The Perils of Pauline]]'' (1967) - Pauline\n*''[[Evil Roy Slade]]'' (1972, TV Movie) - Betsy Potter\n*''[[Agatha (film)|Agatha]]'' (1979) - Pierrot #2\n*''[[No Surrender (film)|No Surrender]]'' (1985) - Organist\n*''[[The Dressmaker (1988 film)|The Dressmaker]]'' (1988) - Singer (final film role)\n\n===Television===\n*''[[Screenplay (TV series)|Screenplay]]'' (1980)\n*''[[List of Columbo episodes#Season 1|Columbo: Blueprint for Murder]]'' (1972)\n*''[[Love American Style]]'' (\"Love and the Phone Booth\"; 1969)\n*''[[Rowan & Martin's Laugh-In]]'' (six episodes; 1968)\n*''[[It Takes a Thief (1968 TV series)|It Takes a Thief]]'' (\"Hans Across the Border\", part 1 & 2) (1968)\n*''[[The Virginian (TV series)|The Virginian]]'' (\"Girl on the Glass Mountain\") (1966)\n*''[[The Wild Wild West]]'' (\"The Night of the Whirring Death\"; 1966)\n*''[[My Three Sons]]''  (\"Robbie and the Chorus Girl\"; 1965)\n*''[[The Twilight Zone (1959 TV series)|The Twilight Zone]]'' (\"[[Number 12 Looks Just Like You]]\"; 1964)\n*''[[The Fugitive (TV series)|The Fugitive]]'' (\"Come Watch Me Die\"; 1964)\n*''[[Wagon Train]]'' (\"Molly Kincaid Story\"; 1963)\n*''[[77 Sunset Strip]]'' (\"Reunion at Balboa\"; 1963) \n*''[[77 Sunset Strip]]'' (\"The Steerer\"; 1962) \n*''[[Surfside 6]]'' (\"Prescription for Panic\"; 1961)\n*''[[Lawman (TV series)|Lawman]]'' (\"Jailbreak\";1962)\n\n==Personal life==\nAustin married Charles W. Britt in Santa Clara, California on October 27, 1963; they had one child, a son, Beau C. Britt (born June 17, 1964). Austin and Britt divorced later that year.\n\nShe married, secondly, to Guy Franklin McElwaine (a Hollywood press agent) in Los Angeles on July 17, 1965. They divorced in June 1967. She married Leopold S. Wyler in Los Angeles on January 9, 1974.<ref name=\"glamourgirlsofthesilverscreen\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0042487}}\n*{{IBDB name|97958}}\n*{{Youtube|tZQbuk6_opE|1966 Dodge Rebellion campaign promo}}\n*{{Youtube|Dg8HN7Ht_TA|1967 Dodge Polara advertisement featuring Pamela Austin}}\n*{{Youtube|NTf9GdsMahI|1967 Dodge Dart TV ad & Pamela Austin tribute}}\n*[http://elviswomen.greggers.net/austinpam.htm Fansite profile]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Austin, Pamela}}\n[[Category:1941 births]